\begin{slide}
\section{Stochasticity}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item A chemical equation
    \begin{align*}
      A + B \goesto{k_1} C
    \end{align*}
    happens when molecule $A$ by chance hits molecule $B$ with the right
    momentum\pause
  \item If the number of molecules are large then we can model this
    quite accurately by considering an ODE of what happens on
    average\pause
  \item But for proteins and other molecules in the cell we often have a
    rather small number of a particular species of molecule in the
    cell\pause
  \item In this case the ODE can be misleading\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Stochasticity in Nature}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Randomness can be problematic in making a system function\pause
  \item Where this is critical then the cell relies on large molecule
    number\pause
  \item However, there are times when randomness can serve a
    purpose\pause
  \item In a large population of cells there can be an advantage to
    cells being in slightly different states\pause
  \item This can give more robustness when responding to external
    stimuli\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Sources of Noise}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item There are some variations that are common to most reactions
    coming from e.g.
    \begin{itemize}\squeeze
    \item number of RNA-polymerase 
    \item number of ribosomes
    \item size of cell
    \end{itemize}
  \item This is known as \emph{extrinsic noise}\pause
  \item There is also noise due to the inherent randomness of chemical
    processes such as transcription and translation---this is known as
    \emph{intrinsic noise}\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}


