\begin{slide}
\section[-1]{Rescaling}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item When we are working with ODEs we can work in any units of
    concentration and time\pause
  \item Note that we can change our units of concentrations by a
    rescaling $X_i \rightarrow r\,X_i$\pause
  \item If we rescale $K\rightarrow r\,K$, $t\rightarrow r\,t$,
    $k_i\rightarrow k_i/r$ for $i\in\{3,4,5\}$ this leaves the ODEs
    invariant
    {\small \begin{align*}
      \frac{\dd [X_1(t)]}{\dd t} &= \frac{k_1}{1+([X_2(t)]/K)^n} - k_3 \,
                                 [X_1(t)]- k_5\,[X_1(t)] \\
       \frac{\dd [X_2(t)]}{\dd t} &= k_2 + k_5\,[X_1(t)] - k_4\,[X_2(t)]\pause
    \end{align*}}
  \item When going to numbers $[X_i(t)]=X_i/\Omega$ by choosing $r$ we
    can explore systems with the same mean concentration but different 
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}


