\begin{slide}
\section{Limitations}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Computers are very fast and can happily simulate millions of
    steps\pause
  \item However, some chemical equations can happen millions of time
    faster than others\pause
  \item We need to run long enough to capture the slowest
    processes\pause
  \item If we are unlucky then this can be just too slow\pause
  \item We can sometimes cheat and approximate large jumps for fast
    moving processes\pause
  \item We can also assume that the fast processes have reached a
    quasi-equilibrium (plus some noise)\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Using Gillespie Equations}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Gillespie algorithm provides the best approximation to the true
    dynamics\pause
  \item Of course, being entirely numerical it doesn't provide much
    insight into how changes in parameters change the dynamics\pause
  \item It is often used to check how accurate the ODE description
    is\pause
  \item There is a well developed system of stochastic differential
    equations which bridges the gap between Monte Carlo simulation and
    ODEs, but it is technically challenging (beyond this course) and it
    is not easy to apply to these systems (it requires putting in
    the size of fluctuations which can be very difficult to
    estimate)\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% Next Slide %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{slide}
\section{Conclusions}

\begin{PauseHighLight}
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Chemical reactions are stochastic\pause
  \item In small systems with low concentrations this can lead to large
    fluctuations\pause
  \item Populations of cell are empirically found to have large
    fluctuations between individuals\pause
  \item Often this is used to ensure that different cells do different
    things\pause
  \item We can use Gillespie's algorithm to accurately simulate
    fluctuations in chemical equations\pause
  \end{itemize}
\end{PauseHighLight}

\end{slide}
